```
function flipLights(n: number, m: number): number {

    // Some observations:
    // Combination of 1 - 4 operations

    // Flip all and Flip even numbers = Flip odd numbers
    // Flip all and Flip odd numbers = Flip even numbers
    // Flip odd ande even numbers = Flip all
    // if n < 3, Flip 3k + 1 numbers = Flip odd numbers

    // => 1 + 2 = 3
    // => 1 + 3 = 2
    // => 2 + 3 = 1
    // => n < 3, 4 = 2

    // n = 0 or m = 0, only 1 state (initial state)
    if (n == 0 || m == 0) return 1;

    // n = 1, only 2 state
    if (n == 1) return 2;

    // n = 2, m = 1
    // we cound have 4 operations:
    // flip all => 00
    // flip odd => 01
    // flip even => 10
    // flip 3k + 1 => 01
    // 2 and 4 are the same, so we have 3 states
    if (n == 2 && m == 1) return 3

    // n = 2, m = 2
    // possible operations:
    // 1 + 1 => nothing change,     11 -> 00 -> 11
    // 1 + 2 => 3, flip odd,        11 -> 00 -> 01
    // 1 + 3 => 2, flip even,       11 -> 00 -> 10
    // 1 + 4 => 2, flip even,       11 -> 00 -> 10
    // 2 + 3 => 1, flip all,        11 -> 10 -> 00
    // 2 + 4 => 1, flip all,        11 -> 10 -> 00
    // 3 + 4 => nothing change,     11 -> 01 -> 11
    // added one more state on top of m = 1, so m = 2, 4 states

    // based on the above, we can conclude that:
    // 1 + 2 = 3
    // 1 + 3 = 2
    // 2 + 3 = 1

    // n = 2, m > 2
    // 1 + 2 + 1 = 3 + 1, flip odd
    // 1 + 3 + 1 = 2 + 1, flip even
    // not gonna list all of them, but you got the idea:

    // for m >= 2, the possible states are 4
    if (n == 2 && m >= 2) return 4;

    // Say, n = 3, m = 1
    // flip all     =>      111 -> 000
    // flip odd     =>      111 -> 010
    // flip even    =>      111 -> 101
    // flip 3k + 1  =>      111 -> 011
    // could have 4 states, this is a general rule for all n > 2
    if (n > 2 && m == 1) return 4;

    // Say, n = 3, m = 2
    // 1 + 1                        111 -> 000 -> 111
    // 1 + 2 = 3, flip odd,         111 -> 000 -> 010
    // 1 + 3 = 2, flip even,        111 -> 000 -> 101
    // 1 + 4,                       111 -> 000 -> 100
    // 2 + 3 = 1, flip all,         111 -> 101 -> 000
    // 2 + 4                        111 -> 101 -> 001
    // 3 + 4                        111 -> 010 -> 110
    // could have 7 states, this is a general rule for all n > 2 and m = 2
    if (n > 2 && m == 2) return 7;

    // n = 3, m > 2
    // 1 + 2 + 4 = 3 + 4            111 -> 000 -> 010 -> 110
    // 1 + 3 + 4 = 2 + 4            111 -> 000 -> 101 -> 001
    // 1 + 4 + 1 = 4                111 -> 000 -> 100 -> 011
    // 2 + 4 + 1 = 3 + 4            111 -> 101 -> 001 -> 110
    // 3 + 4 + 1 = 2 + 4            111 -> 010 -> 110 -> 001
    // added one new possible state on top of m = 1, we got 8 states here
    // not gonna list all, but you got the idea:
    // for m > 2, we could simpify it to the base case m = 2
    // e.g. 1 + 4 + 2 + 3 
    //      => simpify 2 + 3 to 1           => 1 + 1 + 4
    //      => 1 + 1 is doing nothing       => 4
    if (n == 3 && m > 2) return 8;

    // for n > 3, m > 2 it is same as n = 3
    if (n > 3 && m > 2) return 8;

    // we can simplify the above findings to the follows but I would keep it to teach the future me
    if (n == 0 || m == 0) return 1;
    else if (n == 1) return 2;
    else if (n == 2 && m == 1) return 3;
    else if (m == 1) return 4;
    else if (m == 2) return 7;
    else return 8;

};
```

