# Approach
This is highly observation based problem. 
We can note that if n is 1 we can only have 2 states (0,1) if we have presses>0. 
We then can observe that, when we have n = 2, if presses == 1 we will have (11,01,10). But if we have presses == 2 we have all 4 combinations (00,11,01,10).

We then can observe that if n = 3, if we have presses == 1 we will have 4 unique states (111,010,101,100). If presses == 2 we will have ((111,101,010),000,011,110) 7 states and if presses >= 3 we have ((111,101,010),000,011,110,100,001) all 8 possible states.

But now if we observe for n == 4, if presses == 1 we have same 4 states (1111,0101,1010,1001). For presses == 2 we have ((1111,0101,1010),0000,0110,1100,0011). For presses == 3 we have (((1111,0101,1010),0000,0110,1100,0011), 1001) and for presses == 4,5.. we have same states.

This trend continues for any n >= 3. Hence we follow the above code.

