# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Situation 1 `n===1`: Button 1,3,4 are the same, So 2 types of button in total. `t(1) = 2`
Situation 2 `n===2`: Button 3,4 are the same, So 3 types of button in total. `t(2) = 3`
Situation 3 `n>=3`: 4 button has different outcome. So 4 types of button. `t(n) = 4, n>=3`.

**Important:** Based on observation
1. Press any button twice equals not press anything.
2. The sequence of press button will not impact outcome. Means press `Button 1 -> Button 2` equals `Button 2 -> Button 1`.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
When `presses == 0 `, no state change, all lights are on. Just `1` status.
`flipLights(n, 0) = 1`, when `n >= 1`

When `presses >= 1`:
1. `presses == 1`.

`flipLights(n, 1) = t(n)` where `t(1) = 2, t(2) = 3, t(i) = 4 (i>2)`.

2. `presses == 2`.
Situation 1 `n===1`: `flipLights(1, 2) = C(t(1),2) + flipLights(1, 0) = 1 + 1 = 2`.
Situation 2 `n===2`: `flipLights(2, 2) = C(t(2),2) + flipLights(2, 0) = 3 + 1 = 4`.
Situation 3 `n>=3`: `flipLights(n, 2) = C(t(n),2) + flipLights(n, 0) = 6 + 1 = 7`.


`C(n, r)` is the combination formula, `n` is the size of set, `k` is the size of permutation.
For example, `C(t(3), 2) = C(4, 2)` means, when there are 3 lights, we have 4 different buttons in total, we need to press 2 buttons. So we choose 2 different buttons to press from a total of 4 buttons. That's 6 different combinations.

3. `presses >= 3`.
We can have it in general.

`flipLights(n, presses) = C(t(n), presses) + flipLights(n, presses-2)`.

When `t(n) < presses, C(t(n), presses) = 0`, we will get `flipLights(n, presses) = flipLights(n, presses-2)`. It happens when `presses >= 5`. 

So all we need to do is to analyse and get the below table.

n | presses 0 | presses 1 | presses 2 | presses 3 | presses 4 | presses >= 5| ...
--- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | ---
1 | 1 | 2 | 2 | 2 | 2 | 2 | 2...
2 | 1 | 3 | 4 | 4 | 4 | 4 | 4...
Larger than 3 | 1 | 4 | 7 | 8 | 8 | 8 | 8...

# Complexity
- Time complexity: `O(1)`
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: `O(1)`
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

