# Code 1(Single Array)
```
class Solution {
public:
    int findNumberOfLIS(vector<int>& nums) {
          int n=nums.size();
          vector<pair<int,int>>lisfq(n);
        lisfq[0].first=1;
        lisfq[0].second=1;
        int lo=1;
        for(int i=1;i<nums.size();i++){
            int mx=0;
            int c=1;
            for(int j=0;j<i;j++){
                if(nums[j]<nums[i]){
                    if(lisfq[j].first>mx){
                        mx=lisfq[j].first;
                        c=lisfq[j].second;
                    }
                    else if(lisfq[j].first==mx){
                      c=c+lisfq[j].second;
                    }
                }
            }
           lisfq[i].second=c;
            lisfq[i].first=mx+1;
            if(lo<lisfq[i].first){
               lo=lisfq[i].first; 
            }
        }
        int count=0;

        for(int i=0;i<nums.size();i++){
            if(lisfq[i].first==lo){
                count+=lisfq[i].second;
            }
        }
        return count;
    }
};
```
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

1. The solution uses two arrays, `lis` and `fq`, to keep track of the length of the longest increasing subsequence ending at each index and the count of such subsequences respectively.

2. Initialize the `lis` array with all elements set to 0, and set the first element of `lis` and `fq` to 1 since the LIS for a single element is always 1, and there is one such subsequence.

3. Iterate through the `nums` vector from index 1 to the end:

   a. For each element at index `i`, find the maximum length of the LIS ending at index `i` and store it in `lis[i]`. Also, keep track of the count of such LIS in the `fq[i]` array.

   b. To find `lis[i]` and `fq[i]`, loop through the elements before index `i` (j varies from 0 to `i-1`):

      - If the element at index `j` is less than the element at index `i`, it means we can form a longer LIS ending at index `i` by appending the element at index `i` to the LIS ending at index `j`.

      - Update `lis[i]` and `fq[i]` based on the maximum LIS found so far and the count of LIS ending at index `j`.

      - If the LIS ending at index `j` has the same length as the current maximum (`lis[j] == mx`), update the count of LIS ending at index `i` by adding the count of LIS ending at index `j`.

4. After the iteration, the variable `lo` will store the length of the longest increasing subsequence present in the given vector `nums`.

5. Iterate through the `lis` array again to find the count of LIS with length `lo`, and accumulate the count in the `count` variable.

6. Return the value of `count` as the final result, representing the number of Longest Increasing Subsequences in the input vector.

Overall, the solution uses dynamic programming to efficiently compute the count of Longest Increasing Subsequences. It finds the length of the LIS and its count for each element in the `nums` vector, and then calculates the total count of the longest increasing subsequences with the maximum length. 

