solutions.content:
Define `dp_l(i)` as the length of the longest increasing subsequence in `nums[:i + 1]`.
Also, define `dp_c(i)` as the number of the longest increasing subsequence in `nums[:i + 1]`.
Then we'll get the recursion below:
`dp_l(i) = max(dp_l(j) + 1, dp_l(i)) for j in range(i)`
`dp_c(i) += dp_c(j) if dp_l(i) == dp_l(j) + 1`

```python
class Solution:
    def findNumberOfLIS(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:
        if not nums:
            return 0
        n = len(nums)
        dp_l = [1] * n
        dp_c = [1] * n
        for i, num in enumerate(nums):
            for j in range(i):
                if nums[i] <= nums[j]:
                    continue
                if dp_l[j] + 1 > dp_l[i]:
                    dp_l[i] = dp_l[j] + 1
                    dp_c[i] = dp_c[j]
                elif dp_l[j] + 1 == dp_l[i]:
                    dp_c[i] += dp_c[j]
        max_length = max(x for x in dp_l)
        count = 0
        for l, c in zip(dp_l, dp_c):
            if l == max_length:
                count += c
        return count
```

