# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
EX: a1= [1,3,5,4,7]
   normalise this to a2= [0,1,3,2,4]
answer for a1 = answer for a2 .
why? because only quantity changed,but not relative order.
consider this a part 1.
use sorting, map to normalise.
Now u have part 1 .
let us define our dp state.
   dp[i]= stores  two values 
      1) len of longest strictly increasing subsequence ending at i.
      2) How many sequences of this above length are there, which    are ending at index i.

How to fill this dp table .
  two ways 
   1) O(n*n)  , for each i , check the dp[j] 's where 0<=j<i and a2[j]<a2[i].  and fill correspondingly.,
   2) O(n*logn) , use segment tree 

    for dp[i] , find(the max len and count of those max len sequences. which are ending with value strictly less than a2[i])


Lastly why even part1?
   i am storing their values in segment trees , so to minimise the space of segment trees.

This is the idea.
  think for a minute and implement yourself in you way.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
segment trees to fill dp[i] in log(n)

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(n*logn)$$


- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(n*logn)$$

