Before you read this, please make sure you already know the LIS O(NlogN) solution!

Refer : https://leetcode.com/problems/longest-increasing-subsequence/discuss/1303416/longest-increasing-subsequence-in-onlogn

So in the O(NlogN) solution, we created a DP array where the index at which we landed on using lower_bound function gave us the length of the Longest Increasing Subsequence ending current element.

Now Here, we will modify this approach to solve for number of LIS by (read this carefully) : Storing the counts of LIS ending at current element.  

Suppose the current element is 4 and lower_bound gives us 3, that mean LIS of length 3 can be formed by ending at 4. To get count, We know that we can place 4 after any of the LIS of length 2 that end with an element smaller than 4. 

We can create a List of List of Pairs, vector<vector< pair<int,int> >> LISbylen(N+1); in which we store the ( count of LIS end at current element, and the current element ). So to get the count we can add up the counts of LIS of len-1 where the last element is smaller than current element.


	int findNumberOfLIS(vector<int>& nums) {

        int n = nums.size();

        vector<int> dp(n+1, INT_MAX);
        vector<vector< pair<int,int> >> LISbylen(n+1);

        dp[0] = INT_MIN;
        LISbylen[0] = { {1, INT_MIN} };

        int max_len = 1;
        for(auto &ele: nums){

            int len = lower_bound(dp.begin(), dp.end(), ele) - dp.begin();
            dp[len] = ele;

            int ele_count = 0;
            for(auto &[count, last]: LISbylen[len-1])
                if(ele>last) ele_count+=count;

            LISbylen[len].push_back({ele_count, ele});
            max_len = max(max_len, len);

        }

        int num_lis = 0;
        for(auto &[count, last]: LISbylen[max_len])
            num_lis += count;

        return num_lis;

    }

