solutions.content:
**Approach**
First things first, I store all the trees to be cut in a vector and sort them so as to traverse linearly. Then, i check for the base-case where the starting point is a wall, if true return -1.

Then, i iterate through the vector, with the initial starting point as {0,0} and target point as the location of the tree with smallest height of the vector sorted in ascending order which is at 0th index.

Then, as i iterate i update the starting point as the previous target point and target point as the location of the current tree to be cut. Then, i perform an iterative bfs call and if the result is -1, meaning the tree couldn't be reached anyhow, return -1 otherwise add up the result.

In bfs function, i check for the base case when starting point and target point are same, return 0 if true. I store the location in a queue, a typical data structure used for bfs traversal. I create a boolean visited vector of same dimensions as that of grid. Initially, i push the starting point and mark it as visted. Then, i perform a level by level bfs traversal where i increment moves for every level, check if the unvisited non-wall neighbour cell is the target cell, if true, return moves. Else mark the parent as well as neighbouring cell as visited and if out of bounds, check for the next neighbour.

If the queue gets empty without returning moves, means we weren't able to reach the target, in that case, return -1.


**Code**
```
class Solution {
public:

    int cutOffTree(vector<vector<int>>& grid) {

       vector<pair<int,pair<int,int>>> v;
        for(int i=0;i<grid.size();i++){
            for(int j=0;j<grid[0].size();j++){
                if(grid[i][j]>1)
                    v.push_back({grid[i][j],{i,j}});
            }
        }

        if(grid[0][0]==0)return -1;
        int ans=0;
        sort(v.begin(),v.end());
        int m=grid.size(),n=grid[0].size(),tx,ty;

            for(int i=0,sx=0,sy=0;i<v.size();i++){


                tx=v[i].second.first,ty=v[i].second.second;


                int result=bfs(grid,sx,sy,tx,ty);

                if(result==-1)return -1;
                else ans+=result;

                sx=tx,sy=ty;
            }
            return ans;

    }


private:

    int bfs(vector<vector<int>>& grid,int& sx,int& sy,int& tx,int& ty){
        if(sx==tx and sy==ty)return 0;
        queue<pair<int,int>> q;
        int m=grid.size(),n=grid[0].size();
        vector<vector<bool>> vis(m,vector<bool>(n,false));
        //stack<pair<int,pair<int,int>>> st;
        q.push({sx,sy});
        vis[sx][sy]=true;
        int moves=0;

        while(!q.empty()){
            moves++;

            int si=q.size();

            vector<int> dir={-1,0,1,0,-1};

            while(si--){
                int i=q.front().first,j=q.front().second;
                vis[i][j]=true;

                q.pop();
                if(i==tx and j==ty){
                    return moves-1;
                }

                for(int a=0;a<4;a++){
                    int r=i+dir[a],c=j+dir[a+1];

                    if(r<0 or c<0 or r>=m or c>=n or grid[r][c]==0 or vis[r][c])
                        continue;

                    vis[r][c]=true;
                    q.push({r,c});
                }

            }
        }
        return -1;
    }
};
