# Intuition
Because we have to go from smallest to largest - need to sort by tree height and then use this information to count min steps using Dijkstra between each point.
**let me know if this gets TLE, I will remove it not to confuse people**
# Approach
Sort cells by height (excluding 0 and 1)
start from point 0, 0 and count steps  to get to cells which trees need to be cut.
for each pair perform Dijsktra to get min steps and add to the total steps until you get to the cell with the highest tree

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
adding to sorted points = nmlog(mn)
calculate distance for all mn and and for dijkstra mn+mnlogmn  = nm*(nmlogmn) = n^2m^2logmn 
- Space complexity:
min heap and min heap +visited array temp for dijkstra = mn

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int cutOffTree(List<List<Integer>> forest) {       
        PriorityQueue<int[]> pq = new PriorityQueue<>((a,b)->(Integer.compare(a[2], b[2])));
        int m = forest.size();
        int n = forest.get(0).size();
        //define order of cells to cut min heap
        for(int i=0; i < m; i++){
            for(int j = 0; j < n; j++){
                if(forest.get(i).get(j) >= 2){
                    pq.add(new int[]{i,j,forest.get(i).get(j)});
                }
            }
        }
        //start from 0,0 count min steps to reach what's in heap
        pq.add(new int[]{0,0,0});
        int minSteps = 0;        
        while(!pq.isEmpty()){
            int[] curr = pq.poll();
            if(pq.isEmpty())
                break;
            int[] next = pq.peek();
            //once reached remove from pq and aim for the next one
            int steps = reachSteps(curr, pq.peek(),forest);
            if(steps == Integer.MAX_VALUE)
                return -1;
            minSteps += steps;
        }        
        return minSteps;
    }

    private int reachSteps(int[] start, int[] goal, List<List<Integer>> forest){
        int minSteps = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        PriorityQueue<int[]> pq = new PriorityQueue<>((a,b)->(Integer.compare(a[2], b[2])));
        boolean[][] visited = new boolean[forest.size()][forest.get(0).size()];
        pq.add(new int[]{start[0], start[1], 0});
        int[] xd = {-1, 0, 1, 0}; 
        int[] yd = { 0, 1, 0,-1};
        while(!pq.isEmpty()){
            int[] curr = pq.poll();
            if(visited[curr[0]][curr[1]])
                continue;
            visited[curr[0]][curr[1]] = true;
            if(curr[0] == goal[0] && curr[1] == goal[1])
                return minSteps = curr[2];
            for(int i=0; i < 4; i++){
                int newX = curr[0]+xd[i];
                int newY = curr[1]+yd[i];
                if(newX >= 0 && newX < forest.size() && newY >=0 && newY < forest.get(0).size() && !visited[newX][newY] && forest.get(newX).get(newY) > 0){
                    pq.add(new int[]{newX, newY, curr[2]+1});
                }
            }
        }
        return minSteps;

    }
}
