# Approach
* According to the problem statement, if a cell has a tree, then we can either choose to cut it or not cut it and if we cut the tree, the value of the cell becomes 1 and it can still be walked on. Hence it means that we can walk on any cell that initially has a value greater than or equal to 1 as many times as we want.
* The only restriction that we have is the order of cutting the trees, we have to cut the trees from shortest to longest but it doesn't mean that we are not allowed to take a path that consists of that cell.
* Let the trees sorted by their height be t1, t2, t3, t4, ........
* Since we start from the cell (0, 0), we first have to find the shortest path from (0, 0) to t1. The shortest path between (0, 0) and t1 can consist of any cell that doesn't have the value 0. (Remember, we are only not allowed to cut a longer tree before a shorter tree, but we can still freely walk on them). We can find the shortest path using BFS.
* After going to tree t1, we cut the tree and now we will go to the tree t2. We can again use BFS to find the shortest path from t1 to t2.
* Similarly, we find the shortest path between t2 to t3, t3 to t4 and so on cutting those trees along the way.
* Let the shortest distance between (0,0) and t1 be d1, t1 and t2 be d2, t2 and t3 be d3 and so on.....
* The answer will be the sum of all those shortest distances d1 + d2 + d3 + .....

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O((m*n)^2)$$
- Space complexity: $$O(m*n)$$

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int cutOffTree(vector<vector<int>>& forest) {
        int m=forest.size(), n=forest[0].size();

        // find all the trees
        vector<vector<int>> trees;

        for(int i=0; i<m; i++) {
            for(int j=0; j<n; j++) {
                if(forest[i][j] > 1) {
                    trees.push_back({forest[i][j], i, j});
                }
            }
        }

        // sort the trees in increasing order of their heights
        sort(trees.begin(), trees.end());

        auto bfs = [&](int sx, int sy, int tx, int ty) {
            // find the shortest distance between the source and target
            vector<pair<int,int>> moves{{1,0},{-1,0},{0,1},{0,-1}};
            bool visited[m][n];
            memset(visited, false, sizeof visited);
            queue<pair<int,int>> queue;

            visited[sx][sy] = true;
            queue.push({sx, sy});
            int depth = 0;

            while(not queue.empty()) {
                for(int t=queue.size(); t>0; t--) {
                    auto [x, y] = queue.front();
                    queue.pop();

                    if(x==tx and y==ty) return depth;

                    for(auto [dx, dy] : moves) {
                        int nx = x + dx;
                        int ny = y + dy;

                        if(nx>=0 and nx<m and ny>=0 and ny<n
                           and forest[nx][ny]>=1 and not visited[nx][ny]) {
                               visited[nx][ny] = true;
                               queue.push({nx, ny});
                           }
                    }
                }

                depth++;
            }

            return -1;
        };

        int dist = bfs(0, 0, trees[0][1], trees[0][2]);
        if(dist == -1) return -1;

        int result = dist;

        for(int i=0; i<trees.size()-1; i++) {
            int dist = bfs(trees[i][1], trees[i][2], trees[i+1][1], trees[i+1][2]);
            if(dist == -1) return -1;
            result += dist;
        }

        return result;
    }
};
```

